\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
Over the past few years, generative models including diffusion models [] and flow models [] have emerged as the dominant paradigm in modern generative AI, demonstrating unprecedented capability in synthesizing high-fidelity visual content across various modalities []. While pre-training on large-scale datasets enables these models to capture complex data distributions, aligning them with human preference and specific downstream constraints remains a critical challenge. Recently, Reinforcement Learning (RL) based fine-tuning [] like Direct Policy Optimization (DPO) [] and Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) [] has proven effective in bridging this gap, enabling the optimization of models against reward models [] that faithfully reflect human preference.
Among these advancements, Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) [] has stood out for its efficiency and stability.
Initially grounded in Large Language Models (LLMs) [], GRPO estimates the advantage of each sample relative to a group average under a given condition (e.g., a textual prompt), thereby eliminating the need for a complex value network and fostering a scalable, flexible framework for preference alignment.
A line of researches [] have adapted GRPO for visual generation by substituting the standard ODE solvers with SDEs to introduce stochasticity during the flow sampling process.
% Given that flow models involve costly iterative denoising to synthesize clean data,
Given that the reward can only be calculated on noise-free data obtained through costly iterative denoising,
it is crucial to maximize the utility of these hard-earned samples through comprehensive evaluation.
However, existing methods typically operate under a "Single-View" paradigm: they evaluate the generated group solely against the original forward condition.
We reinterpret this evaluation protocol as
% \textbf{a highly stochastic, one-to-many mapping from the condition space $\mathcal{C}$ to the data space $\mathcal{X}$},
\textbf{an under-specified, one-to-many mapping from the condition space $\mathcal{C}$ to the data space $\mathcal{X}$},
as shown in Fig. [] (a). This formulation is inherently sparse and brittle, evidenced by the instability of reward rankings, as depicted in Fig. []. Specifically, it is observed that even slight perturbations to the input text condition lead to substantial shifts in the reward ranking of the generated group from a single SDE rollout.
% , a phenomenon that remains consistent across multiple reward models.
Such phenomenon remains consistent across multiple reward models.
This can be attributed to the high semantic density possessed by visual samples, which is difficult to validly interpret via a single condition descriptor. Consequently, relying exclusively on the initial, single condition for advantage estimation fails to capture the fine-grained relationships and intrinsic quality nuances among the generated samples, resulting in insufficient and unstable exploration.
In light of these issues, we posit that a better GRPO paradigm necessitates a shift from sparse, single-view supervision to a dense, multi-view one. Since the condition space $\mathcal{C}$ essentially forms a continuous semantic manifold, we can effectively densify the condition-data reward signal by sampling a cluster of semantically adjacent descriptors around the original condition anchor. By utilizing this augmented set of conditions to jointly evaluate the same generated group, a dense mapping can be created to offer a more comprehensive understanding of the relative advantages among samples, as illustrated in Fig. [] (b).
Based on the above analysis, we propose \textbf{M}ulti-\textbf{V}iew \textbf{GRPO} (\textbf{MV-GRPO}), a novel reinforcement learning framework that instantiates this dense supervision paradigm via an Augmented Condition Space.
% Specifically, MV-GRPO integrates a pre-trained Vision-Language Model as an \textbf{Inverse Operator} into the training loop. For each generated group, the inverse operator projects the sampled images back onto the condition manifold to retrieve a set of posterior descriptors.
Specifically, MV-GRPO introduces a flexible \textbf{Condition Enhancer} module that can be implemented in two complementary modes: (1) an online \textit{Vision-Language Model (VLM)} that projects generated images back onto the condition manifold to retrieve posterior descriptors, and (2) an offline \textit{Large Language Model (LLM)} that expands the prior condition space via semantic rewriting.
These augmented descriptors, along with the original condition, form a multi-view condition cluster used to jointly evaluate the relative advantage relationships among the generated samples. Our paradigm offers two key benefits: (i) First, the multi-view evaluation mitigates the brittleness of single-condition assessments, providing a comprehensive consensus that stabilizes the optimization process. (ii) Second, by augmenting the condition space $\mathcal{C}$ rather than the computationally expensive data space $\mathcal{X}$, our method also serves as a sample diversity booster with negligible overhead. Extensive experiments demonstrate that MV-GRPO significantly outperforms standard single-view baselines, achieving superior convergence stability and generalization capabilities on both in-domain metrics and out-of-domain benchmarks. Our contribution can be summarized as follows:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Dense Multi-View Mapping}: We identify the sparsity and brittleness of the "Single-View" evaluation in GRPO for flow models and propose a dense, multi-view supervision paradigm via augmenting the condition space.
    \item \textbf{MV-GRPO}: We present MV-GRPO, a novel GRPO framework that leverages an online/offline Condition Enhancer to construct an augmented condition manifold, establishing a multi-view consensus that effectively enhances the policy optimization and alignment performance.
    \item \textbf{Superior Performance}: MV-GRPO achieves superior performance over existing baselines, excelling in both in-domain and out-of-domain evaluation.
\end{enumerate}
